-----------------------------------------
6. map vs unordered_map
-----------------------
map:
- Ordered
- O(log n)
- Red-Black Tree

unordered_map:
- Unordered
- O(1) average
- Hash Table

Use:
map → sorting required
unordered_map → fast lookup required

-----------------------------------------
7. Important Behavior of []
--------------------------------
m[key] inserts key if not present

Example:
cout << m[10]; // inserts 10 with default value

Safe:
m.at(key); // throws error if not found

-----------------------------------------
8. Iteration
-------------
for(auto it : m)
    cout << it.first << " " << it.second;

Gives sorted order

-----------------------------------------
9. Advantages
--------------
- Sorted keys
- No duplicates
- O(log n) guaranteed
- Good for range queries

-----------------------------------------
10. Disadvantages
-----------------
- Slower than unordered_map
- Higher memory usage

-----------------------------------------
11. When to use map?
--------------------
Use when:
- Sorting required
- Ordered traversal needed
- Range queries needed

Avoid when:
- Only fast lookup needed

